      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Noise and Nuisance Disclosure When Selling Brisbane Property
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Brisbane sellers have specific noise and nuisance disclosure obligations. Here is what counts as a material fact, which local noise sources require disclosure, and how to handle it in a way that protects you legally without undermining your campaign.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Noise is one of those issues that sellers in Brisbane's inner east sometimes try to manage by hoping buyers will not notice. The suburb boundary is near a flight path corridor. The neighbour runs a licensed venue. The train line at the end of the street is busier on weekday mornings than most buyers expect. The thinking goes: buyers can hear it at an open home, so they can draw their own conclusions. That logic does not hold up legally, and it does not hold up commercially either.</p>

      <p>Queensland contract law requires sellers to disclose any material fact, which is defined broadly as any fact a reasonable buyer would want to know before entering a contract. Noise and nuisance clearly fall within that definition when they are persistent, ongoing, or significantly affect the enjoyment of the property. The test is not whether the buyer could have discovered it themselves. The test is whether a reasonable buyer would consider it relevant to the decision to purchase and at what price.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What counts as a material noise or nuisance fact</h2>
      <p>Not every sound needs to be documented in a disclosure. The threshold is materiality: whether a reasonable buyer would consider it significant enough to affect their purchasing decision or the price they would pay. In practice, the following categories consistently meet that threshold in Brisbane's inner east and should be disclosed rather than left for buyers to discover on their own.</p>

      <p>Proximity to Brisbane Airport flight paths is one of the most common issues in suburbs along the northern and southern corridors. Properties in Hamilton, Bulimba, Hawthorne, Morningside, Murarrie, and several surrounding areas sit under approach and departure paths. Flight frequency varies by wind direction and operational decisions at the airport, which means a property can be quiet on the day of an open home and noticeably louder on a weekday morning. Buyers and their solicitors know to check the Brisbane Airport noise register, and sellers in affected suburbs are better placed to disclose it directly than to let buyers find it independently mid-contract.</p>

      <p>Licensed entertainment venues are a material noise source in suburbs like Fortitude Valley, West End, Teneriffe, and parts of New Farm. If your property is within earshot of late-night noise from a venue operating under a liquor licence, that is something a buyer moving from a quieter suburb would reasonably want to know. The fact that the noise is generated by a business operating lawfully does not remove the seller's disclosure obligation.</p>

      <p>Industrial or commercial neighbours, train lines, bus depots, and ongoing construction all follow the same logic. A train line two streets away that runs freight services from 5am is a different living experience from a property where that line does not exist. A commercial food operator with early morning deliveries in an otherwise residential street affects sleep in a way buyers want to know about before signing.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Disclosed versus undisclosed: the legal difference</h2>
      <p>Sellers who stay silent about known noise or nuisance issues are not in a neutral position. A buyer who discovers a material noise issue after settlement, and can demonstrate the seller was aware of it and failed to disclose it, has grounds to seek rescission of the contract or damages. Rescission effectively unwinds the transaction. The legal process is protracted, expensive, and stressful even when the seller ultimately prevails. It is not an outcome worth risking for the sake of avoiding a disclosure conversation.</p>

      <p>The contrast with proactive disclosure is significant. A seller who discloses a known noise factor in writing, before the contract is signed, has discharged their obligation. The buyer has acknowledged the issue, made their decision with full information, and cannot later claim they were misled. That is the outcome a disclosure-first approach produces.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to disclose: the practical process</h2>
      <p>Disclosure should be in writing and should occur before the contract is signed, not during negotiations or after the buyer has already committed emotionally to the purchase. A disclosure made too late, or delivered verbally at an open home without written confirmation, is difficult to enforce and easy to contest. Written confirmation, whether as a note in the contract, a pre-contract disclosure letter, or a written communication to the buyer's solicitor, creates a clear record that the information was provided.</p>

      <p>The Brisbane Airport noise register is publicly accessible, and solicitors acting for buyers in flight path suburbs routinely check it. Sellers who are aware their property sits in a noise-affected zone should not wait for the buyer's solicitor to raise it. Getting ahead of it, noting the flight path proximity in the pre-contract disclosure, and explaining what the noise is actually like in practice gives buyers accurate context rather than leaving them to form worst-case assumptions.</p>

      <p>What to document: keep a copy of every written communication in which you disclosed a noise or nuisance matter. If the disclosure is part of a formal contract special condition, retain a signed copy. If it was communicated by email, retain the thread. The documentation does not need to be elaborate, but it does need to exist and be retrievable if the matter is ever revisited after settlement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How an agent presents noise factors without tanking buyer interest</h2>
      <p>There is a significant difference between disclosing a noise issue and leading with it in a way that frames your property negatively. An experienced agent will disclose accurately while also providing context: how often the noise occurs, what mitigations are already in place (double glazing, insulation, vegetation screening), and what the realistic impact on daily life actually is. A property under a flight path corridor that has double-glazed windows and an insulated roof already deals with the most intrusive part of the noise. A venue nearby that operates only on Friday and Saturday nights is a different proposition from one that operates seven nights a week until 3am.</p>

      <p>Buyers respond better to honest disclosure that includes context than to disclosure that feels like a confession. An agent who handles it well can present the noise factor as a known, managed element of the property rather than as a hidden flaw that has been reluctantly revealed. That approach protects the seller legally and does not materially harm the result with buyers who are genuinely suited to the property.</p>

